03536nam a22004695i 9780804768238DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047682387 a10.1515/97808047682382doi  a(DE-B1597)581302  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHM1272.D45 2007eb 7aSOC0430002bisacsh04a305.8009731 aDhingra, Pawan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aManaging Multicultural Lives :bAsian American Professionals and the Challenge of Multiple Identities /cPawan Dhingra. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b6 tables, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction: Opening Up the Margins in the Mainstream -- t2 Uncovering Asian Americas: Examining Korean Americans and Indian Americans in Texas -- t3 Growing Up Takes (Identity) Work: Developing Ethnic Identities -- t4 Model Americans and Minorities: Racial Identities and Responses to Racism -- t5 Multiculturalism on the Job: The Work Domain -- t6 Aspiring to Authenticity: The Home Domain -- t7 Becoming Cultural Citizens: The Leisure and Civil Society Domains -- t8 Conclusion: Reconciling Identities, Recognizing Constraints -- tAppendix: Questions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do people handle contrasting self-conceptions? Do they necessarily compartmentalize their personal lives from their professional lives? Do minority and immigrant groups, in particular, act "ethnic" at home, "American" at work, "racial" in pan-ethnic spaces? Managing Multicultural Lives moves past this common assumption and demonstrates how minorities actually bring together contrasting identities. Using the words and experiences of Indian American and Korean American professionals themselves, Pawan Dhingra eloquently shows how people break down the popular "margins vs. mainstream" conception of group identity and construct a "lived hybridity." He offers new insight into minorities' experiences at work, at home, and in civil society. These Asian Americans' ability to handle group boundaries fluidly leads them to both resist and support stratified social patterns. It also indicates new, more nuanced understandings of immigrant adaptation, multiculturalism, and identity management that pertain to multiple types of immigrant groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aSociology -- Immigration. 4aSociology -- Race, Class, and Gender. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476823840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768238423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768238/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles